AhmedHadi8408/30/25 06:58

Black Sea isn't your typical fresh aquatic scent. Instead, it feels like a night sea, where cold, salty minerals mix with warm, smoky resins.
The scent creates a mysterious marine mood, blending fog, wet wood, and grey amber.
You first notice a flash of citrus—bitter orange and bergamot—mixed with black pepper and a salty, briny note that hints at waves hitting your skin.
Next, you get seaweed and marine herbs, a gentle herbal bitterness from myrtle and rosemary, and a hint of metallic ozone.
Here, the fragrance declares its difference: the sea here feels alive and full of energy, not just clean and simple. Sperm whale amber, labdanum resin, and salt-etched woods (cedar/guaiac) with a warm leather trace and a light smoke-like scent, reminiscent of damp wood starting to ignite.
It’s a mix of salt, smoke, and amber, moving from the chill of beach metals to a warm, mysterious feeling like late-night fires by the shore.

Longevity: 8–10 hours on skin, and may extend longer on fabric.
Sillage: moderate leaning towards strong in the first two hours, then settles into a near-medium aura.
The fragrance line is present and clear in air-conditioned indoor spaces; outdoors, its trace remains attractively salty and woody.
Excellent for summer and spring evenings, and mild autumn nights; in hot summer days, it can be intense if over-sprayed.
Wearing this scent adds style to smart-casual or relaxed formal outfits, especially when paired with dark colours and crisp shirts.
This is for anyone looking for a mature marine scent that's more dramatic and deep than typical fresh blue perfumes.
It suits both men and women with a clear masculine leaning.
If you enjoy Pazzaglia's darker scents or like the idea of an amber night sea, Black Sea is worth trying.
And if you're looking for a straightforward, refreshing scent, this one might feel too deep in the "aquatic" category.
A beautiful balance between salty minerals and warm resin; a distinctive character.
Outstanding performance for such a style.
Weaknesses:
The opening's iodine/mineral aspect may seem "brutal" to those seeking a clean, easy-wearing marine scent.
It requires measured doses in extreme heat. Based on my personal experience in Iraq's hot climate, the suggested spraying method would be three to four sprays (neck, behind the ears, chest/collar) in the evening.
You might also try a light layer underneath the fragrance of "dry citric cologne" if you wish to soften the saltiness during the day.
In the end, I say...
Black Sea by Lorenzo Pazzaglia turns the sea from a calm postcard into a nighttime scene, with sharp salt, warm smoke, and driftwood.
This is a moody fragrance with strong character and artistic style, perfect when you want a deeper, more serious take on the sea.

Ahmed Hadi – Baghdad – IRAQ

frankcoelho10/08/24 11:19

Dark blue salty abyssal fragrance. This is the summary of my experience with the fragrance.

Supporting citrus tone to an oceanic scent. I pick up the plant-like green touch the myrtle brings to the fragrance but in a powdery way, especially through the first hour. The lack of citruses, if you so wished to find here can be found in Sex-Sea also by LP, they are similar in construction but sex-sea is much less mature.

Performance is stellar! Nothing extreme/suffocating but I'm able to smell myself way past the 4th hour of wearing it. Will stay on skin for over 8h and will for sure allow for others to smell you with great sillage and projection.
Now, I don't support blind buying this as, to some, it may be too salty. However, I get a well balanced experience with nothing being too over the top!

Price point is okay I'd say, 50ml for ~150 is what I paid and will last a long time as probably 8 sprays is the most I can pull off with this when outside but typical 5-6 indoor will get you plenty of time on skin. Avoid clothes as the fragrance will stick after good 1-2 washes.

This is a must sample, to say the least. In the Sea line, my order is Sex-Sea, Black Sea, Dream Sea, and Artik Sea from the ones I've tried.

Emorandeira04/08/24 09:42

I am not a big lover of marine fragrances and therefore this is one of the reviews that IS more difficult to me to write about the Discovery set.

Despite not being my favorite perfumes, I have found along the way some that have captivated me like Megamare by Orto Parisi, a marine bomb that lasts all day and projects kilometers; or The Saint mariner by Parfumerie particuliere, a marine perfume full of elegance.

However, this perfume has not captivated me. I didn't dislike it either and I think it has enough differentiating elements to not give it a bad grade. Also it is not the typical marine fragrance, but it has much more, but for me it is a "just good".

Ambergris, musk, salt, orange blossom and moss... That would be the key to this Perfume for me. Within its aquatic and marine charge it also presents a dark and slightly animalic side, probably produced by the mixture of ambergris and musk.

The mixture of these notes with moss produces a seaweed-like aroma, green and salty, which extends throughout the duration of the perfume.

The performance, as in most perfumes that I have tried from the brand, is quite moderate for being an extrait. A powerful and intense output that immediately descends to a medium projection aroma that lasts for about 6 hours.

In my opinion it is not similar to megamare but is more along the lines of a more concentrated Acqua di Gio perfume and subtracts from the citrus part.

It is not a fragrance that I would buy but I can recognize the high quality.

If you like this type of perfume, do not hesitate to try it, but yes, to avoid frustration and disappointment, do not buy it blindly and keep in mind that:

- On many skins, at least mine, the performance is not as good as many say, if what you are looking for is something that lasts a long time and projects intensely, there are other better options.

- It is not a typical marine fragrance. The floral, amber and animalic part has a lot of weight to the detriment of the usual citrus part.

- It has nothing to do with megamare, so if you like megamare you don't have to like this one or vice versa

Perhaps my least favorite of Lorenzo Pazzaglia's marine collection

buzz7206/15/22 08:03

Black Sea by Lorenzo Pazzaglia

Black Sea is a transcendental journey into a vortex sea of summer delights. The opening of Black Sea sends you on a white sandy beach surrounded by tropical fruit trees whilst gazing at the infinite sea. Don't think sweet or coconut notes, they are not here.

The blend of Black Cypriot Salt in Black Sea is heavy as it's found in the top & middle notes but it's so beautifully done it almost becomes like a creamy texture on your skin after emerging out of the sea water with the ylang ylang, orange blossom and a heavy does of ambergris, Sardinian Myrtle, algae to along with a base note of white musk, patchouli and oakmoss. Utterly hypnotic.

The fragrance on skin looks like oil with a whopping concentration of 40%. Longevity and Silage are off the charts but it's so pleasant to wear you almost want to keep it a secret and tell nobody why your skin smells so amazing.

Black Sea by Lorenzo Pazzaglia is often compared to Megamare by Orto Parisi or Acqua Di Sale by Profumum Roma.
I can assure that Black Sea is a completely different experience from both. I own various aquatics and this one just completely stands out from other aquatic fragrances. It's not overwhelming and is a compliment magnet.

Still in doubt?
Jack Daniels and Yamazaki 12 year old whiskies both smell of whisky but do I really need to tell you which is the best? 😊

Black Sea is an aquatic Masterpiece for aquatic connoisseurs.
